    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoyadventurista.com/2015/06/swimming-whale-sharks-donsol-sorsogon-bicol-adventures.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Adventurista',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Donsol Whale Shark Interaction: A Calm DIY Guide to Swimming With Butanding',
        'slug' => 'donsol-whale-shark-interaction-diy-guide',
        'excerpt' => 'Donsol in Sorsogon is the most ethical place in the country to swim with butanding. Here is how to plan the trip without overthinking it, with notes on the rules that keep the industry alive.',
        'content_html' => '<p>Donsol earned its title as the Whale Shark Capital of the World because the butanding actually show up. The town is at the mouth of a plankton-rich gulf in Sorsogon, and from November to June the gentle giants come in to feed. Peak months are February to April, with March usually giving you the best sightings.</p><p>The Donsol interaction is the responsible kind: no chumming, no feeding, no touching, snorkel only, and the boats are required to keep a respectful distance. That is exactly why the population still comes back year after year. Respect the rules and you protect the whole town.</p><h2>How the Interaction Works</h2><p>You register at the Donsol Tourism Office in the morning, watch a short orientation, then board a bangka with a Butanding Interaction Officer (BIO) and a spotter. The boat heads out into the bay and the spotter scans for the silhouettes. When a sighting is called, the BIO tells you to slip into the water quietly and snorkel toward the path of the whale shark, never on top of it.</p><h3>What to Pack</h3><ul><li>Snorkel set, mask, and fins (rental is on-site if you skip)</li><li>Rashguard or sun shirt, the boat ride has no shade</li><li>Reef-safe sunscreen with zinc oxide</li><li>Underwater camera or GoPro, no flash</li><li>Cash for the boat, BIO, and environmental fees</li></ul><h2>When to Go</h2><p>The official season runs November to June. December to March is peak. By May the water starts to warm and the sightings thin out. Avoid the July to October typhoon window because the seas get rough and most boats stay docked.</p><h3>Morning Is the Move</h3><p>Boat trips leave from around 7:30 a.m. and the visibility drops as the sun climbs. Be at the tourism office by 7 a.m. to register, even if you booked through a hotel. The afternoon slots exist but the sightings are noticeably fewer.</p><h2>Getting There</h2><p>Fly to Legazpi from Manila. Both <a href="https://www.cebupacificair.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Cebu Pacific</a> and Philippine Airlines run the route, around 60 minutes, hourly during the day, with one-way fares often landing in the budget range if you book early. From Legazpi airport, ride a van to Donsol Tourism Office. Travel time is roughly an hour, and shared vans wait at the airport curb.</p><p>If you would rather take the long road, <a href="https://www.philtranco.com.ph" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Philtranco</a> and DLTB run overnight buses from Cubao and Pasay to Sorsogon, with a transfer at Daraga or Legazpi for Donsol-bound vans. Travel time is around 12 hours.</p><h2>Pair It With a Firefly Tour</h2><p>The Donsol River firefly cruise leaves after sunset from the same town and pairs perfectly with the daytime butanding trip. The paraw glides up a mangrove river and the trees light up like Christmas. Quiet, slow, and very different from the morning adrenaline.</p><p>For nearby places to sleep in Donsol and around Sorsogon City, you can compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g1016344-Donsol_Sorsogon_Province_Bicol_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. Staying in Donsol itself shaves the morning commute, but Sorsogon City has the wider food scene.</p><h2>The Quiet Rule</h2><p>Stay quiet in the water. Do not splash, do not chase, and never try to ride the butanding for a photo. The spotters can revoke your interaction privilege on the spot. The town gets one shot at protecting these animals, and the traveler choice to follow the rules is what makes the next visitor possible.</p><p>Donsol is one of those Philippine trips where the kwento sticks. Grabe the size of the animal up close, calm as a moving wall. Pack light, listen to the BIO, and let the spotter do the work.</p><p class="source-credit"><em>Inspired by and adapted from <a href="https://www.pinoyadventurista.com/2015/06/swimming-whale-sharks-donsol-sorsogon-bicol-adventures.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Pinoy Adventurista</a>.</em></p>',
        'meta_title' => 'Donsol Whale Shark Interaction DIY Guide | Resort Guru PH',
